-- 1. [Problem Restatement] For a prime p ≥ 7, show that S := Σ_{i=1}^{p-2} i^{-1}(i+1)^{-1} ≡ 2 (mod p). 2. [Key Idea] Note that i^{-1}(i+1)^{-1} equals the telescoping difference i^{-1} – (i+1)^{-1}; summing these differences collapses the series to the first minus the last term. 3. [Proof] For 1 ≤ i ≤ p–2 we have, in ℤ_p, i^{-1} – (i+1)^{-1} = ((i+1) – i)/(i(i+1)) = 1/(i(i+1)) = i^{-1}(i+1)^{-1}. Hence S = Σ_{i=1}^{p-2} [i^{-1} – (i+1)^{-1}] = (1^{-1} – 2^{-1}) + (2^{-1} – 3^{-1}) + ⋯ + ((p-2)^{-1} – (p-1)^{-1}) = 1^{-1} – (p-1)^{-1} (telescoping). Because 1^{-1} = 1 and (p-1) ≡ –1 ⇒ (p-1)^{-1} ≡ –1 (since (–1)·(–1) = 1), we get S ≡ 1 – (–1) ≡ 2 (mod p). 4. [Conclusion] The given sum always equals 2 modulo the prime p ≥ 7.
